      "role": "user",
      "content": "the sock thing makes sense but its still a bit weird. i read somewhere that einstein called it 'spooky action at a distance' cuz he didnt like how it worked. why did he think it was spooky though? like what was the actual problem with it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein was puzzled by quantum entanglement because it seemed to defy the very fabric of his understanding of the universe. He called it 'spooky action at a distance' because it suggested that particles could instantly affect each other without any physical connection, which seemed to violate the principle of locality. In Einstein's view, information couldn't travel faster than the speed of light, and this instantaneous connection between entangled particles appeared to contradict that. He was uncomfortable with the idea that the universe had hidden rules that didn't align with his theory of relativity, which was based on the speed of light being the ultimate speed limit. Einstein believed that there must be some hidden variables, some secret recipe that determined the outcome of these experiments, but the quantum world seemed to resist that idea, leaving him with a sense of unease about the true nature of reality.",
